	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				This spell was seemingly worthless when I first purchased it but it has become very valuable since I have gotten past the levels where I am in Newbie zones hunting skeletons.  After you leave the zones to go hunting bigger and better things your supply of bone chips is very important.  At level 17 this spell heals about 10% of my pets HP every cast which is pretty good for saving bone chips.  At this level 25 mana points is not a lot to spend.  I cast Engulfing Darkness on a yellow or red mob (mostly Dry Bone Skeletons) then follow up with Heat Blood and Heart Flutter, also Leach if I need the extra HP or extra DOT on the MOB.  I then either cast Dark Pact or Start Healing my pet.  When the pet is fighting the 10% healing will keep him near the same level of HP that he is at while the DBS or whatever you are fighting is getting weaker and weaker from the stacked DOTs.  This will keep your pet alive and save you bone chips...and the mana cost to cast it two or three times during a battle is not much...I usually then back off and cast Dark Pact and start medding (of course sitting down to meditate is a HUGE taunt so you will want to back of quite a bit if the MOB is over 40% health.)<BR>
<BR>
Having a pet with at least 50% HP is valuable if you get attacked while medding since it can fight for a while if you do not have enough mana to kill it, you will have a good head start to the zone point for when your pet dies.  A good tactic is to turn off your pets taunt {/pet no taunt} so the MOB chases you and gets hit in the back from your pet...by the time you get to the zone you may be able to melee the MOB enough to kill it or cast a DOT and back off and run again.  This reverse kiting works well with the Darkness line of spells that have a snare effect.<BR>
<BR>
Taek, Dark Elf Necromancer of the 17 season<BR>
Mithaniel Marr Server
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
